// TCP echo server -- grown incrementally across several sessions rather
// than split into separate examples (see CLAUDE.md's TCP section for why):
// unlike ARP/ICMP, TCP's stages (handshake -> data echo -> close) share
// one connection's state and can't be tested independently as separate
// binaries. Regression granularity instead comes from accumulating
// independent test functions in scripts/tcp_echo_test.py, one per stage,
// all run against this same kernel.
//
// Session 1: three-way handshake (LISTEN -> SYN_RCVD -> ESTABLISHED).
// Session 2: data echo once ESTABLISHED -- a received segment carrying
// data from the recorded connection, with the expected next sequence
// number, gets ACKed and echoed back verbatim in a single PSH|ACK reply.
// Session 3 (this one): connection close. A FIN from ESTABLISHED is
// answered with a combined FIN|ACK (ACKing the client's FIN and sending
// our own FIN in the same segment, since we never have unsent data of our
// own queued up -- real stacks do this too when there's nothing left to
// send), moving to LAST_ACK. The client's ACK of that FIN moves back to
// LISTEN, freeing the connection for a new client -- there is no
// CLOSE_WAIT/FIN_WAIT distinction here because both sides' FINs are
// combined into one segment instead of being independent events.
//
// Listens on TCP port 7 (the "Echo Protocol", RFC 862 -- a fitting choice
// for what this will become). Single connection only: while a handshake
// is in progress or a connection is established, SYNs from other clients
// are ignored rather than queued. Out-of-order data (seq != conn_rcv_nxt)
// is silently dropped rather than buffered or explicitly NAKed -- no
// retransmission timer exists on the sender side of this test harness, so
// reordering never actually happens in practice here. A FIN arriving
// together with its own data in the same segment is not supported -- the
// data is simply not echoed, only the FIN is processed -- since nothing
// in this test suite sends that combination.
//
// Single shared file for both targets -- see examples/net_echo/net_echo.tkb's
// header comment for why.
//
// SLICE MIGRATION (P4b/P4c): the handshake/close paths (build_syn_ack,
// build_fin_ack, fix_tcp_checksum, the request-checksum span, the TCP
// options skip) follow examples/http_server/http_server.tkb's fully-proven
// template exactly (see its header comment for the technique), and this
// file is --forbid-trap clean (forbid_trap_tcp_echo in run_qemutest.sh).
//
// ONE genuinely relational site remains, in build_data_echo, marked
// `unsafe` rather than left as a silent runtime check: `data_off` (where
// the payload starts, past any options) and `data_len` (how much payload
// there is) are two INDEPENDENTLY-tracked quantities whose combination
// (`data_off + data_len <= frame's capacity`) is exactly the kind of
// two-variable fact plain interval arithmetic cannot carry, even with the
// same-base rule (which needs the offset to be a bare literal or a bare
// variable with its OWN non-negative lower bound, not an expression
// correlated with the base through a THIRD variable like tcp_hdr_len
// here). Confirmed empirically, not just argued: neither clamping
// data_len directly nor bounding the sum `data_off + data_len` with an
// explicit extra `if` closes it (both were tried -- see CLAUDE.md's P4c
// section for the two failed reformulations and exactly why each one
// still overshoots). This is the one case across the whole P4 census that
// would need a genuine relational/difference-constraint domain to prove
// outright; unsafe is the deliberate, visible stand-in until that's
// judged worthwhile.

use "examples/common/inet_checksum.tkb";
use "examples/common/netutil.tkb";

let mut our_mac: [u8; 6];

// IPv4/TCP field offsets (IP_TOTAL_LEN, IP_TTL, ..., TCP_URGENT) come from
// examples/common/netutil.tkb's `use` above -- offsetof(Ipv4Hdr/TcpHdr,
// field)-based, not hand-maintained here (GitHub issue #79 follow-up: this
// file used to redeclare its own copy of every one of these with the same
// hardcoded values, silently redundant with netutil.tkb's canonical
// versions ever since GitHub issue #77's offsetof refactor added them
// there; harmless while duplicate globals compiled silently, but exactly
// the kind of drift the new duplicate-global check exists to catch --
// removed here rather than suppressed).

// TCP_FLAG_*/PROTO_TCP/TCP_ECHO_PORT are wire-VALUE constants compared
// directly against a byte/half-word field, so they take that field's
// natural width (u8/u16) -- unlike the pure offset constants above,
// which are usize (array/slice indexing is usize-only, see CLAUDE.md's
// "Array/Slice Indices Must Be usize" section). ihl/total_len/tcp_len/tcp_hdr_len/
// data_len/data_off below are ALSO u16-based: `len` (net_rx_len()'s
// deliberately-unconstrained i32 device-reported length) is bridged into
// u16 with ONE bridge cast (`as u16`) right after its own range is
// established, and everything downstream inherits u16-based refined
// ranges through ordinary Add/Sub/comparison propagation from there.
// GitHub issue #72: every bridge cast in this file is written as a bare
// `as <base>` -- the target range is inferred from the source's own
// already-proven range rather than restated by hand.
const TCP_ECHO_PORT: u16 = 7;

// Safe upper bound on the echoed payload: 1514 (frame capacity) - 14
// (eth) - 20 (IP) - 20 (TCP, no options in OUR reply) = 1460. Checked
// explicitly in build_data_echo before constructing the reply segment --
// see that function's comment.
const TCP_MAX_PAYLOAD: u16 = 1460;

enum ConnState: u8 {
    Listen;
    SynRcvd;
    Established;
    LastAck;
}

let mut conn_state:       ConnState = ConnState::Listen;
let mut conn_remote_ip:   [u8; 4];
let mut conn_remote_port: u16 = 0;
let mut conn_snd_nxt:     u32 = 0; // our next unacknowledged sequence number
let mut conn_rcv_nxt:     u32 = 0; // next sequence number we expect from remote

// Recomputes the TCP checksum over the pseudo-header implied by `ip` and
// the full segment `tcp_seg` (header + data -- ITS OWN LENGTH, read back
// via tcp_seg.len, is what goes in the pseudo-header's length field, so
// this can never disagree with the segment it's actually checksumming).
// Must be called last, after every other TCP field has its final value.
fn fix_tcp_checksum(ip: borrow [u8; 20..], tcp_seg: borrow [u8; 20..]) {
    write_u16be(tcp_seg[TCP_CHECKSUM..<TCP_URGENT], 0);
    let mut pseudo: [u8; 12];
    slice_copy(pseudo[0..<4], ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST]);
    slice_copy(pseudo[4..<8], ip[IP_DST..<20]);
    pseudo[8] = 0 as u8;
    pseudo[9] = PROTO_TCP;
    write_u16be(pseudo[10..<12], tcp_seg.len as i32);
    let sum: i32 = checksum_add(pseudo as []u8, 0);
    write_u16be(tcp_seg[TCP_CHECKSUM..<TCP_URGENT],
                checksum_fold(checksum_add(tcp_seg, sum)));
}

// Rewrites a SYN request into a SYN-ACK reply in place. Only called from
// TCP_LISTEN after the caller has already validated the request (IP/TCP
// checksums, dst port, SYN flag set).
fn build_syn_ack(eth: borrow [u8; 54..], ihl: {20..<21 as u16}) {
    slice_copy(eth[0..<6], eth[6..<12]);
    slice_copy(eth[6..<12], our_mac as []u8);

    let ip  = eth[14..<34];
    let tcp = eth[34..<54];

    slice_copy(ip[IP_DST..<20],     ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST]);
    slice_copy(ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST], OUR_IP as []u8);
    ip[IP_TTL] = 64 as u8;
    write_u16be(ip[IP_TOTAL_LEN..<4], ihl + 20);
    write_u16be(ip[IP_CHECKSUM..<IP_SRC], 0);
    write_u16be(ip[IP_CHECKSUM..<IP_SRC],
                inet_checksum(ip[0..<ihl as usize]));

    let client_port: u16 = read_u16be(tcp[TCP_SRC_PORT..<TCP_DST_PORT]) as u16;
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_SRC_PORT..<TCP_DST_PORT], TCP_ECHO_PORT as i32);
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_DST_PORT..<TCP_SEQ], client_port as i32);
    write_u32be(tcp[TCP_SEQ..<TCP_ACK], TCP_INITIAL_SEQ as i32);
    write_u32be(tcp[TCP_ACK..<TCP_DATA_OFFSET], conn_rcv_nxt as i32);
    tcp[TCP_DATA_OFFSET] = (5 << 4) as u8; // 20-byte header, no options
    tcp[TCP_FLAGS] = TCP_FLAG_SYN | TCP_FLAG_ACK;
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_WINDOW..<TCP_CHECKSUM], 65535);
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_URGENT..<20], 0);

    fix_tcp_checksum(ip, tcp);
}

// Rewrites a received data segment into an ACK|PSH reply carrying the
// same payload verbatim. `data` is a runtime-checked view of where the
// payload actually starts in the received segment (see the file header
// comment for why data_off/data_len can't be jointly proven); our own
// reply always uses a clean 20-byte header with no options, so the
// payload is copied down to eth+54 (tcp+20). slice_copy's forward loop is
// safe here even when the ranges overlap: the destination never leads the
// source (data_off is always >= 34+20, since the received header is at
// least 20 bytes), so by the time a byte is overwritten its original
// value has already been read -- unconditionally, so no `data != tcp+20`
// guard is needed (a same-address copy is just a harmless no-op).
// Only called from TCP_ESTABLISHED after the caller has already validated
// the request and confirmed seq == conn_rcv_nxt. Returns 1 on success, 0
// if data_len somehow exceeded TCP_MAX_PAYLOAD (never actually happens
// given the caller's own tcp_len bound, but see the explicit check below
// for why this needs to be enforced, not assumed, to construct tcp_seg
// with a proven minimum).
fn build_data_echo(eth: borrow [u8; 1514..], ihl: {20..<21 as u16},
        data: borrow []u8, data_len: u16) -> bool {
    // Snapshot into an immutable local after an explicit bound check: a
    // PLAIN u16 PARAMETER carries no range at all (unlike a refined local,
    // parameters can't cross a function boundary with a refined type
    // except by exact match -- see http_server.tkb's
    // `ihl: {20..<21 as u16}`
    // comment for why). This mirrors http_server's HTTP_MAX_PAYLOAD
    // pattern: the check both PROVES tcp_seg's minimum (>= 20, needed by
    // fix_tcp_checksum) and fails safe if data_len is ever larger than
    // this responder's single-segment design supports. data_len is u16,
    // so a hi-only condition is enough to narrow (GitHub issue #99).
    if (data_len <= TCP_MAX_PAYLOAD) {
        let n: u16 = data_len;
        let n_idx: usize = n as usize;
        let tcp_seg = eth[34..<54 + n_idx];

        // Constructed directly from `eth` (literal base 54 = 34+20), NOT
        // by re-slicing tcp_seg[20..<20+n]: tcp_seg's own declared minimum
        // is only 20 (the worst case n=0), so a SECOND subslice built
        // from tcp_seg would lose the connection to n that its own
        // construction above already has. Going straight to `eth` with
        // the same literal-offset same-base shape that proved tcp_seg
        // itself (`eth[34..<54+n]`) proves this one too -- same memory,
        // no unsafe needed.
        slice_copy(eth[54..<54 + n_idx], data);

        slice_copy(eth[0..<6], eth[6..<12]);
        slice_copy(eth[6..<12], our_mac as []u8);

        let ip = eth[14..<34];

        slice_copy(ip[IP_DST..<20],     ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST]);
        slice_copy(ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST], OUR_IP as []u8);
        ip[IP_TTL] = 64 as u8;
        write_u16be(ip[IP_TOTAL_LEN..<4], ihl + 20 + n);
        write_u16be(ip[IP_CHECKSUM..<IP_SRC], 0);
        write_u16be(ip[IP_CHECKSUM..<IP_SRC],
                    inet_checksum(ip[0..<ihl as usize]));

        let client_port: u16 = read_u16be(tcp_seg[TCP_SRC_PORT..<TCP_DST_PORT]) as u16;
        write_u16be(tcp_seg[TCP_SRC_PORT..<TCP_DST_PORT], TCP_ECHO_PORT as i32);
        write_u16be(tcp_seg[TCP_DST_PORT..<TCP_SEQ], client_port as i32);
        write_u32be(tcp_seg[TCP_SEQ..<TCP_ACK], conn_snd_nxt as i32);
        write_u32be(tcp_seg[TCP_ACK..<TCP_DATA_OFFSET], (conn_rcv_nxt as i32) + (n as i32));
        tcp_seg[TCP_DATA_OFFSET] = (5 << 4) as u8;
        tcp_seg[TCP_FLAGS] = TCP_FLAG_ACK | TCP_FLAG_PSH;
        write_u16be(tcp_seg[TCP_WINDOW..<TCP_CHECKSUM], 65535);
        write_u16be(tcp_seg[TCP_URGENT..<20], 0);

        fix_tcp_checksum(ip, tcp_seg);
        return true;
    }
    return false;
}

// Rewrites a received FIN into a combined FIN|ACK reply: ACKs the
// client's FIN (which consumes one sequence number, already folded into
// conn_rcv_nxt by the caller) and sends our own FIN in the same segment.
// Only called from TCP_ESTABLISHED after the caller has already validated
// the request and confirmed seq == conn_rcv_nxt (before incrementing it).
fn build_fin_ack(eth: borrow [u8; 54..], ihl: {20..<21 as u16}) {
    slice_copy(eth[0..<6], eth[6..<12]);
    slice_copy(eth[6..<12], our_mac as []u8);

    let ip  = eth[14..<34];
    let tcp = eth[34..<54];

    slice_copy(ip[IP_DST..<20],     ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST]);
    slice_copy(ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST], OUR_IP as []u8);
    ip[IP_TTL] = 64 as u8;
    write_u16be(ip[IP_TOTAL_LEN..<4], ihl + 20);
    write_u16be(ip[IP_CHECKSUM..<IP_SRC], 0);
    write_u16be(ip[IP_CHECKSUM..<IP_SRC],
                inet_checksum(ip[0..<ihl as usize]));

    let client_port: u16 = read_u16be(tcp[TCP_SRC_PORT..<TCP_DST_PORT]) as u16;
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_SRC_PORT..<TCP_DST_PORT], TCP_ECHO_PORT as i32);
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_DST_PORT..<TCP_SEQ], client_port as i32);
    write_u32be(tcp[TCP_SEQ..<TCP_ACK], conn_snd_nxt as i32);
    write_u32be(tcp[TCP_ACK..<TCP_DATA_OFFSET], conn_rcv_nxt as i32);
    tcp[TCP_DATA_OFFSET] = (5 << 4) as u8;
    tcp[TCP_FLAGS] = TCP_FLAG_FIN | TCP_FLAG_ACK;
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_WINDOW..<TCP_CHECKSUM], 65535);
    write_u16be(tcp[TCP_URGENT..<20], 0);

    fix_tcp_checksum(ip, tcp);
}

fn app_main() {
    uart_puts("tcp_echo: init\r\n");

    match net_init() {
        NetInitResult::Failed => {
            uart_puts("tcp_echo: device/link not found\r\n");
        }
        NetInitResult::Ready(mut ready) => {
            net_read_mac(our_mac as *u8);

            uart_puts("tcp_echo: ready\r\n");

            while (true) {
                net_rx_wait();
                match net_rx_acquire(ready) {
                    NetRxAcquire::None(next) => { ready = next; }
                    NetRxAcquire::Acquired(acquired) => {
                        let len: i32 = net_rx_len(acquired);
                        // The disposition variant replaces the old
                        // should_tx/tx_len integer flag pair: a reply and
                        // its length are now one value, so "flagged but no
                        // length" is unrepresentable.
                        let mut plan: NetRxDisposal = NetRxDisposal::Release;
                        let frame = net_rx_frame(acquired);   // only read when len proves acquisition

                        // 14 (eth) + 20 (min IPv4) + 20 (min TCP) = 54
                        if (len >= 54 && len <= 1514) {
                            // Snapshot into an immutable local: the explicit refined
                            // cast below (len_n as u16) needs to see
                            // len's CURRENT narrowed range, but a function PARAMETER
                            // (always Mut) only exposes its narrowed range through
                            // the separate narrowing_ctx side-table, which a bare
                            // Cast does not consult -- an immutable snapshot's type
                            // inherits the narrowing directly (same "B-plan"
                            // mechanism used elsewhere), so the cast proves clean.
                            let len_n: i32 = len;
                            if (read_u16be(frame[12..<14]) == 0x0800) {
                                let ip = frame[14..<34];
                                // version is standalone (compared only to a literal)
                                // -- safely u8.
                                let version: u8 = ip[0] >> 4;
                                let ihl:     u16 = (ip[0] & 0x0f) * 4;

                                if (version == 4 && ihl == 20) {
                                    // Bridge len_n's proven {54..<1515} range into
                                    // u16 (a free coercion: the source range already
                                    // implies the target range exactly). This bound
                                    // must be kept in sync with the `len >= 54 &&
                                    // len <= 1514` check above.
                                    let len16: u16 = len_n as u16;
                                    let total_len:       u16 = read_u16be(ip[IP_TOTAL_LEN..<4]) as u16;
                                    let ip_len_in_frame: u16 = len16 - 14;

                                    if (total_len <= ip_len_in_frame && total_len >= ihl &&
                                        ip[IP_PROTOCOL] == PROTO_TCP &&
                                        inet_checksum(ip[0..<ihl as usize]) == 0) {
                                        if (slice_eq(ip[IP_DST..<20], OUR_IP as []u8)) {
                                            let tcp:     [u8; 20..] = frame[34..<54];
                                            let tcp_len: u16 = total_len - ihl;

                                            // doff is TCP's own byte-scale field,
                                            // never combined with the ihl/tcp_len
                                            // chain directly (tcp_hdr_len, derived
                                            // from it via Mul, carries its proven
                                            // range across a bridge cast to u16
                                            // below, to match tcp_len for the
                                            // subtraction that follows) -- doff
                                            // itself stays genuinely u8.
                                            let doff: u8 = tcp[TCP_DATA_OFFSET] >> 4;

                                            // doff must be narrowed to {5..<16} BEFORE
                                            // tcp_hdr_len = doff * 4 is computed, so
                                            // Mul propagation gives tcp_hdr_len (and
                                            // later data_off) a real range -- see
                                            // http_server.tkb's identical comment
                                            // (including why the bridge cast below,
                                            // not a plain `as i32`, is needed to
                                            // carry that range across the width
                                            // change -- this file's own data_off use is
                                            // inside `unsafe` so losing the range
                                            // wouldn't have shown up as a trap site
                                            // here, but a plain cast would still have
                                            // been quietly wrong).
                                            if (tcp_len >= 20 && doff >= 5 && doff <= 15) {
                                            let tcp_hdr_len: u16 = (doff * 4) as u16;

                                            if (tcp_len >= tcp_hdr_len) {
                                                let mut pseudo: [u8; 12];
                                                slice_copy(pseudo[0..<4], ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST]);
                                                slice_copy(pseudo[4..<8], ip[IP_DST..<20]);
                                                pseudo[8] = 0 as u8;
                                                pseudo[9] = PROTO_TCP;
                                                write_u16be(pseudo[10..<12], tcp_len);
                                                let sum: i32 = checksum_add(pseudo as []u8, 0);
                                                let tcp_len_idx: usize =
                                                    tcp_len as usize;
                                                let tcp_seg = frame[34..<34 + tcp_len_idx];

                                                if (checksum_fold(checksum_add(tcp_seg, sum)) == 0) {
                                                    let dst_port: u16 = read_u16be(tcp[TCP_DST_PORT..<TCP_SEQ]) as u16;
                                                    let src_port: u16 = read_u16be(tcp[TCP_SRC_PORT..<TCP_DST_PORT]) as u16;
                                                    let flags:    u8  = tcp[TCP_FLAGS];
                                                    let seq:      u32 = read_u32be(tcp[TCP_SEQ..<TCP_ACK]) as u32;
                                                    let ack:      u32 = read_u32be(tcp[TCP_ACK..<TCP_DATA_OFFSET]) as u32;

                                                    if (dst_port == TCP_ECHO_PORT) {
                                                        if (conn_state == ConnState::Listen) {
                                                            if ((flags & TCP_FLAG_SYN) != 0) {
                                                                slice_copy(conn_remote_ip as []u8, ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST]);
                                                                conn_remote_port = src_port;
                                                                conn_rcv_nxt = seq + 1;
                                                                conn_snd_nxt = TCP_INITIAL_SEQ + 1;

                                                                build_syn_ack(frame, ihl);
                                                                plan = NetRxDisposal::Reply(14 + (ihl as i32) + 20);
                                                                conn_state = ConnState::SynRcvd;
                                                            }
                                                        } else {
                                                            // SYN_RCVD, ESTABLISHED, or LAST_ACK: only the
                                                            // recorded connection's segments matter.
                                                            if (slice_eq(ip[IP_SRC..<IP_DST], conn_remote_ip as []u8) &&
                                                                src_port == conn_remote_port) {
                                                                if ((flags & TCP_FLAG_RST) != 0) {
                                                                    // Abrupt close from the client: drop the
                                                                    // connection with no reply and free the slot.
                                                                    conn_state = ConnState::Listen;
                                                                } else if (conn_state == ConnState::SynRcvd) {
                                                                    if ((flags & TCP_FLAG_ACK) != 0 &&
                                                                        (flags & TCP_FLAG_SYN) == 0 &&
                                                                        ack == conn_snd_nxt && seq == conn_rcv_nxt) {
                                                                        conn_state = ConnState::Established;
                                                                    }
                                                                } else if (conn_state == ConnState::Established) {
                                                                    if ((flags & TCP_FLAG_FIN) != 0 && seq == conn_rcv_nxt) {
                                                                        conn_rcv_nxt = conn_rcv_nxt + 1; // FIN consumes one seq number
                                                                        build_fin_ack(frame, ihl);
                                                                        plan = NetRxDisposal::Reply(14 + (ihl as i32) + 20);
                                                                        conn_snd_nxt = conn_snd_nxt + 1; // our FIN too
                                                                        conn_state = ConnState::LastAck;
                                                                    } else {
                                                                        // max(.., 0): tcp_len - tcp_hdr_len's raw
                                                                        // Sub-derived range has a spuriously negative
                                                                        // lower bound (the type system can't see the
                                                                        // tcp_len>=tcp_hdr_len guard that makes a
                                                                        // genuinely negative result impossible), which
                                                                        // would otherwise make data_len look like it
                                                                        // could be negative to any code reading its
                                                                        // type. Clamping to >=0 here doesn't change
                                                                        // observable behavior at all: a malformed
                                                                        // packet where the raw subtraction WOULD have
                                                                        // been negative clamps to exactly 0, and 0
                                                                        // still fails the `data_len > 0` check below
                                                                        // exactly like a negative value would have --
                                                                        // this only makes data_len's OWN type honestly
                                                                        // reflect a fact that was already true, safe
                                                                        // improvement in isolation (P4c section).
                                                                        // data_len/data_off are u16 (matching tcp_len/
                                                                        // tcp_hdr_len's base): both flow into the same
                                                                        // `data_off + data_len` addition below, which
                                                                        // needs them to share a type regardless of the
                                                                        // fact that the access itself is unsafe.
                                                                        let data_len: u16 = max(tcp_len - tcp_hdr_len, 0);
                                                                        let data_off: u16 = 34 + tcp_hdr_len;
                                                                        let data_off_idx: usize =
                                                                            data_off as usize;
                                                                        let data_len_idx: usize =
                                                                            data_len as usize;
                                                                        if (data_len > 0 &&
                                                                            (flags & TCP_FLAG_ACK) != 0 &&
                                                                            seq == conn_rcv_nxt) {
                                                                            // data_off + data_len == 34 + tcp_len always
                                                                            // (algebraic identity: data_off = 34 +
                                                                            // tcp_hdr_len, data_len = tcp_len -
                                                                            // tcp_hdr_len), which fits frame's capacity --
                                                                            // but data_off and data_len are tracked as two
                                                                            // INDEPENDENT ranges, so combining them loses
                                                                            // that correlation even with data_len's own
                                                                            // range now honestly non-negative (confirmed
                                                                            // empirically: even an artificially huge
                                                                            // frame capacity doesn't help once the
                                                                            // correlation is what's missing -- see
                                                                            // CLAUDE.md's P4c section for the exact
                                                                            // numbers). unsafe here is a documented
                                                                            // assertion backed by the `data_len > 0` check
                                                                            // just above, not a guess; this is the
                                                                            // repository's sole executable unsafe site
                                                                            // and would need a genuine
                                                                            // relational/difference-constraint domain to
                                                                            // prove outright, deliberately deferred.
                                                                            let data = unsafe {
                                                                                frame[data_off_idx..<data_off_idx + data_len_idx]
                                                                            };
                                                                            if (build_data_echo(frame, ihl, data, data_len)) {
                                                                                plan = NetRxDisposal::Reply(14 + (ihl as i32) + 20 + (data_len as i32));
                                                                                // conn_rcv_nxt/conn_snd_nxt are u32
                                                                                // (sequence numbers), data_len is u16 --
                                                                                // the widening cast here is harmless
                                                                                // (loses data_len's own refined range,
                                                                                // but neither counter is ever used as a
                                                                                // slice bound/index, so no proof depends
                                                                                // on their refined-ness).
                                                                                conn_rcv_nxt = conn_rcv_nxt + (data_len as u32);
                                                                                conn_snd_nxt = conn_snd_nxt + (data_len as u32);
                                                                            }
                                                                        }
                                                                    }
                                                                } else if (conn_state == ConnState::LastAck) {
                                                                    if ((flags & TCP_FLAG_ACK) != 0 && ack == conn_snd_nxt) {
                                                                        // Close complete; ready for a new client.
                                                                        conn_state = ConnState::Listen;
                                                                    }
                                                                }
                                                            }
                                                        }
                                                    }
                                                }
                                            }
                                            }
                                        }
                                    }
                                }
                            }
                        }

                        ready = net_rx_finish(acquired, plan);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
